1
00:00:01,200 --> 00:00:03,080
INSTRUCTOR: Hello
visitors, it is

2
00:00:03,080 --> 00:00:09,640
time to set up shop with our
Tableau Desktop application,

3
00:00:09,640 --> 00:00:13,840
and that's what this adventure
guide will take you through.

4
00:00:13,840 --> 00:00:18,160
At this point, you should have
requested a student license

5
00:00:18,160 --> 00:00:21,360
for the Tableau
Desktop, and should

6
00:00:21,360 --> 00:00:24,360
have that key and the
ability to download it

7
00:00:24,360 --> 00:00:26,800
onto your own computer.

8
00:00:26,800 --> 00:00:29,240
So I want to take you through
a little bit about Tableau

9
00:00:29,240 --> 00:00:32,659
and why we choose to
use it in this course.

10
00:00:32,659 --> 00:00:37,480
There are lots of great
ways to visualize your data.

11
00:00:37,480 --> 00:00:39,760
Excel is one of the basics.

12
00:00:39,760 --> 00:00:42,920
Power BI is also
created by Microsoft.

13
00:00:42,920 --> 00:00:46,400
There's Domo, which is
located in Silicon slopes,

14
00:00:46,400 --> 00:00:47,960
in the Lehigh area.

15
00:00:47,960 --> 00:00:50,080
And then there's Tableau.

16
00:00:50,080 --> 00:00:52,600
And Tableau is an
industry leader

17
00:00:52,600 --> 00:00:56,680
that's being used by quite a few
companies because of the maps

18
00:00:56,680 --> 00:00:58,760
and dashboard capabilities.

19
00:00:58,760 --> 00:01:02,830
And so we've selected this
platform for this course,

20
00:01:02,830 --> 00:01:04,830
although many of the
concepts you'll be learning

21
00:01:04,830 --> 00:01:09,510
can be transferred to any
visualization that you make.

22
00:01:09,510 --> 00:01:12,370
So Tableau was designed
to solve a problem.

23
00:01:12,370 --> 00:01:14,350
And what was that problem?

24
00:01:14,350 --> 00:01:18,510
It was the barriers in getting
all of that information

25
00:01:18,510 --> 00:01:20,630
into some sort of
a visualization

26
00:01:20,630 --> 00:01:23,590
where we could begin
to see insights.

27
00:01:23,590 --> 00:01:26,670
And so we know that
data is powerful.

28
00:01:26,670 --> 00:01:30,670
We have data, but
there was definitely

29
00:01:30,670 --> 00:01:34,070
a bottleneck in harvesting the
data and getting those insights.

30
00:01:34,070 --> 00:01:36,770
And so not only did Tableau
take advantage of this,

31
00:01:36,770 --> 00:01:39,230
but as I mentioned those
other companies too.

32
00:01:39,230 --> 00:01:41,950
And so there are quite a
few software developers who

33
00:01:41,950 --> 00:01:45,710
are trying to make it
easier for the user

34
00:01:45,710 --> 00:01:49,150
to visualize the massive
amounts of data we have.

35
00:01:49,150 --> 00:01:51,590
So as I mentioned,
right now, they

36
00:01:51,590 --> 00:01:54,670
are the leader in data
flow visualization.

37
00:01:54,670 --> 00:01:57,510
And many companies
do use Power BI just

38
00:01:57,510 --> 00:02:00,310
simply because of the
packaging that you can buy

39
00:02:00,310 --> 00:02:03,090
and bundle, Excel and
Word and so forth.

40
00:02:03,090 --> 00:02:09,330
But Tableau's strength lies
in the map's capability

41
00:02:09,330 --> 00:02:11,210
and in their dashboards.

42
00:02:11,210 --> 00:02:12,950
We'll see what
happens in five years.

43
00:02:12,950 --> 00:02:16,990
It's a market economy, so we'll
see if things change or not.

44
00:02:16,990 --> 00:02:20,750
But it really is
very user friendly,

45
00:02:20,750 --> 00:02:23,410
which is another reason why we
like to use it in this course,

46
00:02:23,410 --> 00:02:25,670
because students with
no prior experience,

47
00:02:25,670 --> 00:02:29,570
even in visualization, can
quickly drag and drop and begin

48
00:02:29,570 --> 00:02:33,490
to feel confident in their
visualization skills.

49
00:02:33,490 --> 00:02:37,110
So Tableau does invest lots
of research and development.

50
00:02:37,110 --> 00:02:40,470
They have an extensive
Tableau help videos,

51
00:02:40,470 --> 00:02:43,050
and I'll show you where
you can find those.

52
00:02:43,050 --> 00:02:47,050
And there's a huge
community of Tableau users.

53
00:02:47,050 --> 00:02:52,250
And so this is a great platform
for us to use in this class.

54
00:02:52,250 --> 00:02:58,210
So there's also a
lot more that Tableau

55
00:02:58,210 --> 00:03:02,450
can be used for
machine learning,

56
00:03:02,450 --> 00:03:05,600
there's statistics natural
language processing,

57
00:03:05,600 --> 00:03:09,800
and basically, its
purpose is to augment

58
00:03:09,800 --> 00:03:12,280
the human creative and
analytical abilities

59
00:03:12,280 --> 00:03:16,120
and to share ideas that promote
the educated use of data.

60
00:03:16,120 --> 00:03:17,620
So that sounds very corporate.

61
00:03:17,620 --> 00:03:20,880
But in reality, if we can
synthesize and understand

62
00:03:20,880 --> 00:03:23,240
our data, even our own
self data, then maybe

63
00:03:23,240 --> 00:03:25,680
we can begin to change
habits that could

64
00:03:25,680 --> 00:03:28,380
lead to healthier happy lives.

65
00:03:28,380 --> 00:03:31,605
Our companies can be more
efficient with their resources,

66
00:03:31,605 --> 00:03:32,480
et cetera, et cetera.

67
00:03:32,480 --> 00:03:34,600
So there's a lot to be learned.

68
00:03:34,600 --> 00:03:38,320
So when we dive
into Tableau, you'll

69
00:03:38,320 --> 00:03:43,162
notice that there are a
couple of different panes.

70
00:03:43,162 --> 00:03:44,620
This is not actually
the home page,

71
00:03:44,620 --> 00:03:46,078
and I'll show you
that in a moment.

72
00:03:46,078 --> 00:03:47,620
But this is the
data source pane.

73
00:03:47,620 --> 00:03:50,640
And you can see that on the
lower left hand corner here,

74
00:03:50,640 --> 00:03:52,180
it says data source.

75
00:03:52,180 --> 00:03:54,740
And this is where you'll
be bringing in your data.

76
00:03:54,740 --> 00:03:57,860
This is one of the places and
probably the primary place.

77
00:03:57,860 --> 00:03:59,480
But this is the data pane.

78
00:03:59,480 --> 00:04:02,400
This left area where it's going
to show the sheets that you

79
00:04:02,400 --> 00:04:06,910
have, and then you can drag them
and drop them into this Canvas.

80
00:04:06,910 --> 00:04:10,070
So that Canvas area does
show that connection

81
00:04:10,070 --> 00:04:15,150
between your sheets and other
sheets that you might bring in.

82
00:04:15,150 --> 00:04:18,390
The Canvas is the logical
layer where you can create

83
00:04:18,390 --> 00:04:20,670
relationships between these.

84
00:04:20,670 --> 00:04:23,190
And then to get to
the physical layer,

85
00:04:23,190 --> 00:04:25,290
you can even double
click this Orders.

86
00:04:25,290 --> 00:04:26,670
It's not live right now.

87
00:04:26,670 --> 00:04:31,110
And then it can open up a
table where you can join

88
00:04:31,110 --> 00:04:35,930
or you can do other types
of relationships there.

89
00:04:35,930 --> 00:04:39,710
This is called the data grid.

90
00:04:39,710 --> 00:04:42,650
And this is where
all of those columns

91
00:04:42,650 --> 00:04:47,870
and rows from your CSV file
or Excel file or JSON file

92
00:04:47,870 --> 00:04:49,150
will be placed.

93
00:04:49,150 --> 00:04:51,410
And we'll get into that
in a little bit more,

94
00:04:51,410 --> 00:04:53,990
but that's called
the data grid area.

95
00:04:53,990 --> 00:04:58,390
And this is the--

96
00:04:58,390 --> 00:05:03,190
oh, I should say for the data
grid that Tableau displays

97
00:05:03,190 --> 00:05:08,310
the first 1,000 rows of data
contained in the data source.

98
00:05:08,310 --> 00:05:10,150
So it only shows
the first 1,000.

99
00:05:10,150 --> 00:05:13,350
So if you have 10,000 rows, it's
not going to show all of those.

100
00:05:13,350 --> 00:05:17,170
But it does reside
within the file.

101
00:05:17,170 --> 00:05:19,490
The next one is the
meta grid table.

102
00:05:19,490 --> 00:05:24,970
And this is showing the fields
that are in your data sources

103
00:05:24,970 --> 00:05:25,870
as rows.

104
00:05:25,870 --> 00:05:29,070
So we have order ID and
you can see order IDs here,

105
00:05:29,070 --> 00:05:31,290
order dates here,
order dates here.

106
00:05:31,290 --> 00:05:33,970
And it begins to tell you
again that physical table,

107
00:05:33,970 --> 00:05:38,270
the remote field and the type,
and so those are also up here.

108
00:05:38,270 --> 00:05:42,390
This is the Tableau workspace.

109
00:05:42,390 --> 00:05:46,290
So this is where you're going
to be spending more of your time

110
00:05:46,290 --> 00:05:50,930
as you drag these
fields onto this Canvas

111
00:05:50,930 --> 00:05:53,690
into the columns or the
rows, and as you begin

112
00:05:53,690 --> 00:05:55,470
to work within this space.

113
00:05:55,470 --> 00:05:57,930
But that's called the
Tableau workspace.

114
00:05:57,930 --> 00:06:01,290
And this is called
the view area.

115
00:06:01,290 --> 00:06:03,850
I did reference
it to the Canvas.

116
00:06:03,850 --> 00:06:06,810
So view or Canvas would be fine.

117
00:06:06,810 --> 00:06:09,240
But that is the
space where you can

118
00:06:09,240 --> 00:06:13,660
begin to make your tables, your
bar charts, your histograms,

119
00:06:13,660 --> 00:06:16,280
your scatter plots, et cetera.

120
00:06:16,280 --> 00:06:18,320
Up here in the
upper left corner,

121
00:06:18,320 --> 00:06:21,600
this is the workbook name
so that you know which

122
00:06:21,600 --> 00:06:23,360
workbook you're working within.

123
00:06:23,360 --> 00:06:25,920
This whole file is the workbook.

124
00:06:25,920 --> 00:06:29,200
And these are the
three shelf cards.

125
00:06:29,200 --> 00:06:32,800
If you will, you've got
pages, filters, and marks.

126
00:06:32,800 --> 00:06:36,120
And those have a lot of
drag and drop capabilities

127
00:06:36,120 --> 00:06:42,920
as you want to filter things or
create pages or the marks card.

128
00:06:42,920 --> 00:06:44,820
These are called the shelves.

129
00:06:44,820 --> 00:06:47,700
And that's where you find
your columns and rows.

130
00:06:47,700 --> 00:06:51,900
So typical when you're
thinking about your xy axis.

131
00:06:51,900 --> 00:06:53,780
So those are the
columns and rows.

132
00:06:53,780 --> 00:06:56,040
And that's called the shelves.

133
00:06:56,040 --> 00:06:58,400
The toolbar is here at the top.

134
00:06:58,400 --> 00:07:02,440
So there's icons that you'll
become more familiar with

135
00:07:02,440 --> 00:07:05,880
to refresh your data to
bring in new data sources

136
00:07:05,880 --> 00:07:09,093
to do ascending versus
descending sorts.

137
00:07:09,093 --> 00:07:10,510
And then there's
also this area up

138
00:07:10,510 --> 00:07:16,110
here where you'll have dropdown
menus to then continue to refine

139
00:07:16,110 --> 00:07:18,990
what your visualizations are.

140
00:07:18,990 --> 00:07:22,350
This little Tableau icon
is the Start Here button.

141
00:07:22,350 --> 00:07:26,790
And so that will return you back
to that main Start Here page

142
00:07:26,790 --> 00:07:30,550
that you'll see when you
first launch Tableau.

143
00:07:30,550 --> 00:07:32,830
Down here at the bottom
is the status bar.

144
00:07:32,830 --> 00:07:37,230
It can tell you where you're
at, and you can't even tell you

145
00:07:37,230 --> 00:07:39,630
how many data points there are.

146
00:07:39,630 --> 00:07:42,570
And you can see that there
are different sheet tabs here.

147
00:07:42,570 --> 00:07:44,590
So the whole thing
is called a workbook.

148
00:07:44,590 --> 00:07:46,310
And these are called sheets.

149
00:07:46,310 --> 00:07:48,690
And there are icons, where
you can add more sheets.

150
00:07:48,690 --> 00:07:51,810
That's this icon this
one with the four grids.

151
00:07:51,810 --> 00:07:54,230
That's actually
for the dashboard.

152
00:07:54,230 --> 00:07:59,550
All right, file
types really quickly.

153
00:07:59,550 --> 00:08:06,350
There's a .twb and this stores a
visualization without the source

154
00:08:06,350 --> 00:08:07,150
data.

155
00:08:07,150 --> 00:08:12,170
Sometimes in this class,
students save .twb because maybe

156
00:08:12,170 --> 00:08:15,370
that was the default setup and
it does not have the source

157
00:08:15,370 --> 00:08:15,870
data.

158
00:08:15,870 --> 00:08:18,100
So when they go to launch
it, it doesn't work.

159
00:08:18,100 --> 00:08:19,350
I'll show you what that means.

160
00:08:19,350 --> 00:08:22,190
But basically there's a file
type with an x at the end.

161
00:08:22,190 --> 00:08:23,390
That's what you need.

162
00:08:23,390 --> 00:08:25,610
But this one has no source data.

163
00:08:25,610 --> 00:08:28,770
The tds, it stores the
server address, password,

164
00:08:28,770 --> 00:08:32,190
and other information
to access a data source.

165
00:08:32,190 --> 00:08:35,289
So if I've got a SQL server
or something else and I need

166
00:08:35,289 --> 00:08:39,230
to create that connection,
I'm going to use .tds.

167
00:08:39,230 --> 00:08:42,929
We won't be using this
extension in our class.

168
00:08:42,929 --> 00:08:47,210
There's the .tbm which stores
a connection to a worksheet

169
00:08:47,210 --> 00:08:49,370
in another Tableau workbook.

170
00:08:49,370 --> 00:08:52,530
So again, when you start
building lots of workbooks

171
00:08:52,530 --> 00:08:55,010
and dashboards, you will
be working with coworkers

172
00:08:55,010 --> 00:08:58,050
potentially where you'll need to
make sure that you're speaking

173
00:08:58,050 --> 00:09:00,490
to one another and
that said .tbm.

174
00:09:00,490 --> 00:09:02,690
We won't be using in that class.

175
00:09:02,690 --> 00:09:09,920
And then you have the .tde where
the Tableau data is filtered,

176
00:09:09,920 --> 00:09:13,080
and there's an
aggregated extract there.

177
00:09:13,080 --> 00:09:14,860
So we will not be
using this either.

178
00:09:14,860 --> 00:09:17,880
This is to speed
connections along,

179
00:09:17,880 --> 00:09:21,800
but it is a way to get the
extracted data that you use.

180
00:09:21,800 --> 00:09:23,560
This is the file
type that you will

181
00:09:23,560 --> 00:09:27,200
be saving 99.9% of the time.

182
00:09:27,200 --> 00:09:31,260
Nothing is really 100%, but
it's called a twbx file.

183
00:09:31,260 --> 00:09:34,680
So the way I pronounce it,
it's a packaged workbook.

184
00:09:34,680 --> 00:09:38,380
It stores the extracted data
and all of your visualizations,

185
00:09:38,380 --> 00:09:41,560
and you can also use it in
the Tableau reader, which

186
00:09:41,560 --> 00:09:46,060
for clients that may not want
to purchase Tableau Desktop,

187
00:09:46,060 --> 00:09:48,280
they can get a free Tableau
reader so they can still

188
00:09:48,280 --> 00:09:53,840
see your visualizations, so
when you save it as a twbx file.

189
00:09:53,840 --> 00:09:55,400
So those are the file types.

190
00:09:55,400 --> 00:09:57,680
This last one, double
check when you're saving

191
00:09:57,680 --> 00:10:00,240
that it has that x on the end.

192
00:10:00,240 --> 00:10:03,240
So there are additional
resources here.

193
00:10:03,240 --> 00:10:07,340
I'll provide this slide
deck in the notes.

194
00:10:07,340 --> 00:10:09,840
But there's different
source 1 and source 2

195
00:10:09,840 --> 00:10:13,690
where you can go check out
stuff in the Tableau help area,

196
00:10:13,690 --> 00:10:17,390
where it points to all this same
information I just outlined.

